<br>
Al'kabor spells suck.<br>
<br>
But, that wasn't news.  =)<br>
<br>
How do you fix them?  I mean, if you just tweak them so their ratio beats out columns on 5 mobs, the'll end up being used for penta-kiting, and almost nothing else.<br>
<br>
You could prevent that pretty easily by using the &quot;half damage on moving mobs&quot; solution, double their current damage, and maybe up the max targets to 6?<br>
<br>
Rains are less of a problem to fix.<br>
<br>
They have massively strignent requirements: wizard/mob placement, they stop doing damage on aggro, require lots of time to do their damage, and have annoying resistance problems.<br>
<br>
Now, I'm guessing that there are people here who have looked at these spells before alot more than me.  Given that caster balancing is going on, isn't this a good time to have a thread talking about this sort of thing?<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrimstafftheurgist.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimstaff Theurgist</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grimicon.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/3/02 9:09:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=722.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/grim3.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Al'kabor and Rains</span><hr size=1> Here's how I'd fix Al'Kabor: Remove target cap, remove &quot;interrupt&quot; which is all but utterly useless in any case.  They have too low damage for the mana to actually get xps using them but without a target maximum they would be able to deal with trains and huge numbers of greens, giving them a use.<br>
<br>
Here's how I'd fix AE Rain spells: Beyond the idiotic &quot;can't kill with the last wave&quot; problem, there's two options.<br>
<br>
The first is my personal favorite, lower the damage slightly post 50 and make them hit with up to 3 waves on up to 4 targets, instead up 4 waves period.  This would require Verant putting more potent blasts at lower level in the 50s to make up for the gap that AE Rains are used to fill.  This would make them all viable AE spells.<br>
<br>
The second is less desired but useful, raise the damage of lower level rains and turn them ALL into single target blasts that act somewhat like a DOT.  Each one has to do at least 1.5 times the damage of the best blast that level, assuming all waves hit for full, to be useful for this.  This would require Verant putting more AE spells in to fill the gaps caused by rains not being there any more (the way they are built now they are barely useful as AE spells in any case).<br>
<br>
Reducing the graphics lag they cause would be another good idea. <p><IMG SRC="http://www.kestrelarts.com/images/book.jpg" ></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/usiryakk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Yakk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/3/02 3:06:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=722.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Target cap</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The first is my personal favorite, lower the damage slightly post 50 and make them hit with up to 3 waves on up to 4 targets, instead up 4 waves period. This would require Verant putting more potent blasts at lower level in the 50s to make up for the gap that AE Rains are used to fill. This would make them all viable AE spells.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Lowering the damage would help.<br>
<br>
The more potent blasts are to replace the use of rain spells as single target nukes, right?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Here's how I'd fix Al'Kabor: Remove target cap, remove &quot;interrupt&quot; which is all but utterly useless in any case. They have too low damage for the mana to actually get xps using them but without a target maximum they would be able to deal with trains and huge numbers of greens, giving them a use.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Silly.  Look for exploits, always.<br>
<br>
Can you kill 1 XP bearing mob using al'kabor?  Then, with that design, you can kill 50 XP bearing mobs using al'kabor.<br>
<br>
It would take a godly manapool, or good mana regen, but... it scales poorly.  You say you can't get XP with it?  feh.<br>
<br>
For example: hand-off kiting.  Get 2 wizards.  One al'kabor kites the 50 mobs until he runs lom.  He then zones as the other one starts kiting the 50 mobs.<br>
<br>
The first one zones back.<br>
<br>
Voila, 25 mobs worth of XP for each wizard.<br>
<br>
Get a larger zone.  Grab 100 mobs.<br>
<br>
50 mobs worth of XP for each wizard.<br>
<br>
AE grouping is sort of balanced, due to the risks of being in melee range, and it requireing 1 or 2 full groups to pull off.<br>
<br>
Because mobs in EQ don't take up space, any infinite-target spell is extremely dangerous.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ukaledin.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kaledin</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_ball.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/3/02 4:27:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=722.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Target cap</span><hr size=1> Too bad VI cant create a Multiple Targeting system.  Where a caster can have hotkey and say be able to typea command like /add &quot;current targets name&quot; and add the creature to a target list etc.  up to say a maximum 6 or 8.   You could then have the Area of effect spells affect only those creatures that are currently targetted consistently, or if the maximum number of targets have not been reached for the spell then a random target in a group of mobs will be hit.  For melee purposes you can only melee attack the primary target, but when it dies, the next target in the list becomes the active target.<br>
Just an idea<br>
<br>
